==Manga==
A month after the release of the PC version of Kin’iro no Corda, the manga adaptation of the game had started to serialize in [[Hakusensha]]’s monthly shōjo manga magazine of [[LaLa]] in October 2003. [[Yuki Kure]], the person who contributed the character designs for the game, authors the manga.

In year 2006, the series has won the Outstanding Debut Award in [[Hakusensha Athena Newcomers' Awards]].

As of March 2011, there are currently 16 volumes of the manga and it’s published under the Hakusensha's shōjo manga imprint, ''Hana to Yume Comics''.<ref name="Japanese volumes">{{cite web
  | title = s-book.net Library Service - 金色のコルダ
  | url= http://www.s-book.net/plsql/slib_series?tid=459218071
  | language= Japanese
  | publisher= s-book.net/Hakusensha
  | accessdate = 2011-03-28}}</ref>

The manga has been licensed by [[Viz Media]] in the [[United States]] under the title, '''''La Corda D’oro'''''.<ref name="English publication">{{cite web
  | title = Viz Media Acquires Lots of Manga
  | url= http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2006-05-01/viz-media-acquires-lots-of-manga 
  | publisher= Anime News Network
  | accessdate = 2009-08-27}}</ref> The first volume was released on October 3, 2006.<ref name="English publication2">{{cite web
 |title      = La Corda d'Oro, Vol. 1
 |url        = http://www.viz.com/products/products.php?product_id=5844
 |publisher  = VIZ Media
 |accessdate = 2009-08-27
}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Chuang Yi]] has also licensed the manga for its English release in [[Singapore]].

